        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Facebook Marketplace</strong> is a built-in e-commerce feature inside Facebook where people and businesses list items for sale, connect with nearby buyers, and complete transactions — either locally in cash or nationwide via Facebook's built-in checkout. It reaches more than 1 billion monthly visitors across 70+ countries and is free to list on for most categories.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Launched</div>
            <div class="tms-value">October 2016</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Social Media</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Monthly visitors</div>
            <div class="tms-value">1 billion+</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">If you sell anything — furniture, cars, clothing, or services — Facebook Marketplace puts your listing in front of buyers who are already on the platform and actively browsing. The question isn't whether to use it, but how to use it so your listings convert instead of sitting idle.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is Facebook Marketplace?</h2>
        <p>Facebook Marketplace is a classifieds-style tab inside the Facebook app and website, accessible via the storefront icon in the main navigation. It launched in October 2016 as a response to the millions of informal buy-and-sell groups already operating on Facebook — and quickly overtook Craigslist as the dominant peer-to-peer marketplace in the US.</p>
        <p>Unlike a standalone platform, Marketplace is embedded in Facebook's social graph. When someone messages you about a listing, they're using Facebook Messenger. When you browse, you see who in your network has also listed or interacted with an item. This social layer is what separates Facebook Marketplace from anonymous classifieds.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Individual sellers</strong> list second-hand goods, vehicles, and rentals</li>
          <li><strong>Small businesses</strong> use it as a free storefront for new inventory</li>
          <li><strong>Enterprise retailers</strong> integrate Marketplace with their Facebook Shops catalog</li>
          <li><strong>Real estate agents and dealers</strong> have dedicated category pages with structured fields</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Facebook's reach advantage</div>
          <p>As of 2024, Facebook Marketplace is available in <strong>70+ countries</strong> and receives over <strong>1 billion monthly visitors</strong>, according to Meta. More than 250 million listings are active at any given time. For local reach, no other social platform comes close.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why Facebook Marketplace matters for businesses</h2>
        <p>Facebook Marketplace isn't just a yard-sale tool. Businesses that treat it as a serious channel consistently outperform those that ignore it:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Free organic reach.</strong> Unlike Facebook's main feed, Marketplace listings are surfaced algorithmically to buyers searching for your category — no ad spend required. A well-optimized listing competes purely on relevance and price.</li>
          <li><strong>Local buyer intent.</strong> People browsing Marketplace are actively looking to purchase. This is pull marketing, not push — conversion intent is significantly higher than social feed browsing.</li>
          <li><strong>Nationwide shipping for physical goods.</strong> Facebook's built-in checkout allows you to ship items and accept payment through Facebook Pay, expanding your reach beyond the local area.</li>
          <li><strong>Vehicle and real estate verticals.</strong> Facebook Marketplace has dedicated sections for cars, trucks, and rental properties, with structured filters that make high-intent searches fast. Dealers using Marketplace consistently report lower cost-per-lead than standalone portals.</li>
          <li><strong>Messenger integration.</strong> Every inquiry arrives in Messenger, where you can use automated replies, saved responses, and lead capture flows — making follow-up systematic rather than manual.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How Facebook Marketplace works</h2>
        <p>Marketplace operates on a combination of location, category, and personalization signals. Here's the transaction flow:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>A seller creates a listing</strong> — title, photos (up to 10), price, description, category, and optional delivery preference (local pickup or shipping).</li>
          <li><strong>Facebook distributes the listing</strong> in the Marketplace feed to nearby buyers, in relevant category searches, and sometimes in Facebook Groups that allow selling.</li>
          <li><strong>Buyers message sellers</strong> through Messenger to ask questions, negotiate, or arrange pickup.</li>
          <li><strong>Transaction happens</strong> — either in-person with cash, or through Facebook Checkout for shipped items (Facebook deducts a 5% selling fee, minimum $0.40 per transaction).</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="url-flow">
